Generic Constraints

Constraints limit the types that can be used with a generic parameter using the `extends` keyword.

### Basic Constraint

```typescript
interface HasLength {
  length: number;
}

function logLength<T extends HasLength>(arg: T): T {
  console.log(arg.length);
  return arg;
}

logLength("hello"); // OK - string has length
logLength([1, 2, 3]); // OK - array has length
// logLength(123); // Error - number has no length
```

### Using keyof in Constraints

```typescript
function getProperty<T, K extends keyof T>(obj: T, key: K): T[K] {
  return obj[key];
}

const person = { name: "Alice", age: 30, email: "alice@example.com" };
const name = getProperty(person, "name"); // string
const age = getProperty(person, "age"); // number
// getProperty(person, "salary"); // Error: "salary" not in keyof
```

### Constraining to Constructor

```typescript
function createInstance<T>(ctor: new (...args: any[]) => T): T {
  return new ctor();
}
```

### Multiple Constraints

```typescript
interface Identifiable {
  id: number;
}

interface Timestampable {
  createdAt: Date;
}

class Entity<T extends Identifiable & Timestampable> {
  constructor(public data: T) {}
}
```

### Conditional Constraints

```typescript
type IsString<T> = T extends string ? "yes" : "no";

type A = IsString<string>; // "yes"
type B = IsString<number>; // "no"
```

> **Key Point:** Constraints ensure generics only accept types that meet specific requirements.

codeExample:
interface Shape {
  color: string;
  area(): number;
}

function describeShape<T extends Shape>(shape: T): string {
  return `A ${shape.color} shape with area ${shape.area()}`;
}

class Circle implements Shape {
  constructor(public color: string, private radius: number) {}
  area(): number {
    return Math.PI * this.radius ** 2;
  }
}

const circle = new Circle("red", 5);
console.log(describeShape(circle));

// Constrained generic with keyof
function pluck<T, K extends keyof T>(items: T[], key: K): T[K][] {
  return items.map(item => item[key]);
}

const users = [{ name: "Alice", age: 30 }, { name: "Bob", age: 25 }];
const names = pluck(users, "name"); // string[]
const ages = pluck(users, "age"); // number[]
